00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:30.119
This is the sixth lesson in the series.

00:00:30.119 --> 00:00:35.870
In this lesson we will continue with the same
topic as in Day 5, Ethernet LAN switching,

00:00:35.870 --> 00:00:40.649
but we will go a little deeper to make sure
there aren’t any holes in your knowledge.

00:00:40.649 --> 00:00:44.850
Once again, we’re talking about sending traffic within a LAN, like between

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:48.230
these three PCs in this small network here.

00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:52.750
The topic of how these PCs could send traffic
out beyond the router to other networks is

00:00:52.750 --> 00:00:58.460
for a future lesson, let’s start locally
first, with LAN switching.

00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:02.660
Before I get started, I want to speak a little
bit more on Ethernet frames which we talked

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:05.220
about in the last video.

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:11.710
The preamble + SFD is usually not considered
part of the Ethernet header, although it is

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:14.030
sent with every Ethernet frame.

00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:20.659
So, the Ethernet header consists of these
three field, destination, source, and type.

00:01:20.659 --> 00:01:25.911
Therefore, the size of the Ethernet header
+ trailer is 18 bytes, if you don’t include

00:01:25.911 --> 00:01:28.500
the preamble + SFD

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:32.090
Now, there is also a minimum size for an Ethernet
frame.

00:01:32.090 --> 00:01:38.840
The minimum size is 64 bytes, including the
encapsulated payload, the packet.

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:44.159
64 bytes minus the 18 bytes of the header
equals 46 bytes.

00:01:44.159 --> 00:01:48.719
Therefore, the minimum payload size is 46
bytes.

00:01:48.719 --> 00:01:54.180
Now, what if we send a payload packet that
is less than 46 bytes?

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:59.750
If the payload is less than 46 bytes, padding
bytes are added, and these bytes are all 0s

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:01.440
by the way.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:06.860
For example, if you send a 34-byte packet,
12 bytes of padding will be added.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:10.580
Okay, that’s all I wanted to add.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:15.170
Remember that the Preamble and SFD might not
be included as part of the Ethernet header,

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:20.080
depending on how you define it, but they are
included with every Ethernet frame.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:25.819
Also, remember the minimum size of the frame,
64 bytes, and that doesnt include the preamble

00:02:25.819 --> 00:02:28.459
and SFD, by the way.

00:02:28.459 --> 00:02:33.580
That means that the minimum payload is 46
bytes, and padding will be added if the payload

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:35.510
is less than that.

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:39.090
Now let’s get started with the main topics
for today’s video.

00:02:39.090 --> 00:02:44.410
So, here’s the same small network we saw
in the previous video.

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:46.070
There are a couple changes, however.

00:02:46.070 --> 00:02:54.080
First, I changed the interfaces from Fastethernet
to gigabit ethernet, hence the G0/0, G0/1,

00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:56.380
and G0/2 for each switch.

00:02:56.380 --> 00:02:59.720
Secondly, look at the mac addresses.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:11.739
In the previous video I used AAAA.AA00.0001,
for PC1, or .0002 for PC2, etc.

00:03:11.739 --> 00:03:15.910
This time let’s use some more realistic
MAC addresses.

00:03:15.910 --> 00:03:20.310
Notice once again that the OUI, the first
half of the MAC address that identifies the

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:28.650
maker of the device, is the same for each
PC, 0C2F.B0, so that means that the PCs were

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:31.500
all made by the same company.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:36.110
Of course, the second half of each device’s
MAC address is unique, since that represents

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:38.680
the device itself.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:43.019
When I refer to these MAC addresses I’ll
just use the last 4 digits, to keep things

00:03:43.019 --> 00:03:44.569
simple.

00:03:44.569 --> 00:03:53.209
For example, I’ll just say PC1’s MAC address
is 9D00, or PC2’s MAC address is 6200.

00:03:53.209 --> 00:03:57.069
Now, let’s add one more thing to this network
topology.

00:03:57.069 --> 00:03:59.750
Let’s add some IP addresses.

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:05.010
We won’t actually talk about the details
of IP addresses in this video, but we’ll

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:08.189
need IP addresses to explain something else
in this video.

00:04:08.189 --> 00:04:17.230
So, this number here, 192.168.1.0/24, represents
this whole network here.

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:22.140
Then .1 represents PC1’s IP address.

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:29.040
This is just the short version, PC1’s real
IP address is 192.168.1.1.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:39.200
PC2’s IP address is 192.168.1.2, PC3’s
IP address is 192.168.1.3, and PC4’s IP

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:44.920
address is 192.168.1.4.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:49.220
Now, in the last video I only really showed
you part of the picture of how these PCs can

00:04:49.230 --> 00:04:52.380
communicate within this network.

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:57.190
When a device sends some data to another device,
it doesn’t just include a source and destination

00:04:57.190 --> 00:04:59.640
MAC address.

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:04.880
Encapsulated within that frame is an Internet
Protocol, known as IP, packet, and that IP

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:09.340
packet includes a source and destination IP
address.

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:18.550
For example, if PC1 wants to send data to
PC3, the source IP will be 192.168.1.1 and

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:23.780
the destination IP will be 192.168.1.3.

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:35.840
The source MAC will be 0C2F.B011.9D00, however
PC1 doesn’t actually know PC3’s MAC address.

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:41.270
When you send data to another computer, you
enter the IP address, not the MAC address.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:49.520
So, the user entered the IP address 192.168.1.3
as the destination, but PC1 has to discover

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:52.000
PC3’s MAC address by itself.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.930
Remember, these switches are Layer 2 devices,
they don’t operate at Layer 3, so they need

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:01.330
to use MAC addresses, not IP addresses.

00:06:01.330 --> 00:06:07.840
So, PC1 wants to send this Ethernet frame
to PC3, but first it has to learn PC3’s

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:09.710
MAC address.

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:16.060
To do so, it uses something called ARP, the
Address Resolution Protocol.

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:19.750
Let’s take a look at ARP.

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:23.500
ARP stands for Address Resolution Protocol.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:28.820
It is used to discover the Layer 2 address,
meaning the MAC address, of a known Layer

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:32.780
3 address, meaning the IP address.

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:41.900
For example, in our example here PC1 knows PC3’s
Layer 3 address, 192.168.1.3, but it doesn’t

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:45.790
know the Layer 2 address, its MAC address,
yet.

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:52.030
The ARP process consists of two messages:
The ARP request, sent by the device that wants

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:54.900
to know the MAC Address of the other device.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:07:01.810
And the ARP reply, which is sent to inform
the requesting device of the MAC address.

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:09.000
In our example, PC1 would send the ARP request,
and PC3 would send the ARP reply.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.810
The ARP request is sent as a broadcast ethernet
frame.

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:17.640
Broadcast means it is sent to all hosts on
the network.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:22.970
Because the Layer 2 address of the destination
host is unknown, it broadcasts the request

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:26.630
and waits for a reply from the correct device.

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:29.300
The ARP reply is unicast.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.820
We learned about unicast frames in the last
video.

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:37.880
A unicast frame is sent to only one host,
in this case its the host that sent the ARP

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:38.880
request.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:42.970
Let’s take a look at how this works on our network.

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:48.170
Here at the bottom is the original frame that
PC1 wants to send to PC3.

00:07:48.170 --> 00:07:51.090
But first, It has to send this frame.

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:53.810
This is an ARP request frame.

00:07:53.810 --> 00:07:59.090
The source and destination IP addresses, as
well as the source MAC address, are the same.

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:02.760
However, look at the destination MAC address.

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:11.040
FFFF.FFFF.FFFF is the broadcast MAC Address.

00:08:11.050 --> 00:08:15.470
This is the destination MAC address used when
a device wants to send ethernet frames to

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.540
all other devices on the local network.

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:23.690
So, PC1 has prepared the Arp request to be
sent.

00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:29.000
It sends the frame out of its network interface,
and it is received by SW1.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.690
SW1 then adds PC1’s MAC address to its MAC
address table.

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:38.190
When a MAC address is learned in this way,
what is it called?

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:43.169
It’s called a dynamic mac address, which
we learned in the last video.

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:50.630
So, since the destination MAC address is all Fs,
SW1 broadcasts the frame out of all of its

00:08:50.630 --> 00:08:54.630
interfaces, except the one it was received
on.

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:59.560
This is very much like what a switch does
with an unknown unicast frame, which we also learned

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:01.940
about last video.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:08.750
It sends the frame out of G0/1 and G0/2, but
not G0/0 because it received the frame on

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:10.390
that interface.

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:14.040
PC2 receives it, but it ignores the frame.

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:19.590
That’s because the destination IP address
doesn’t match PC2’s IP address, so it

00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:26.100
knows that the ARP request is meant for a
different PC, so it just ignores the request.

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:32.640
Of course, then SW2 learns PC1’s MAC Address
and adds it to the MAC address table, associating

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:38.500
it with the G0/2 interface since that’s
the interface the frame was received on.

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:43.740
Since the destination MAC address is the broadcast
MAC address, SW2 also sends the frame out

00:09:43.740 --> 00:09:47.890
of all interfaces, except the one the frame
was received on.

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:53.130
So, that means it sends the frame out of G0/0
and G0/1.

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:59.680
PC4 ignores the frame, because the destination
IP address doesn’t match its own.

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:06.560
However, PC3 recognizes that the destination
IP addresses does match its own IP address,

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:09.650
so it doesn’t ignore the ARP request.

00:10:09.650 --> 00:10:16.310
What it does is send the other ARP message
I mentioned briefly, the ARP Reply.

00:10:16.310 --> 00:10:19.240
Here you can see the ARP reply packet.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:24.050
The source IP is PC3’s IP, and the destination
is PC1’s IP.

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:31.950
The Source MAC is PC3’s MAC address, and
the destination is PC1’s.

00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:37.130
Although the ARP Request message was a broadcast
message, because PC1’s MAC address was used

00:10:37.130 --> 00:10:43.710
as the source MAC address of the ARP request
message, PC3 now knows PC1’s MAC address

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:49.530
so it can send the ARP reply directly to PC1,
without having to broadcast the frame.

00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:55.940
PC3 sends the frame out of its network interface,
and it is received by SW2.

00:10:55.940 --> 00:11:02.690
SW2 learns PC3’s MAC Address and enters
it into the MAC address table, associating

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:06.010
it with the G0/0 interface.

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:11.280
Since this is a unicast frame, and SW2 already
has an entry for the destination MAC address

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:16.830
in its MAC address table, what kind of frame
is this, and what does SW2 do with it?

00:11:16.830 --> 00:11:22.650
It’s a known unicast frame, and SW2 will
simply forward it out of the interface in

00:11:22.650 --> 00:11:27.900
the MAC address table, it will not flood it
like an unknown unicast frame or a broadcast

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:29.570
frame.

00:11:29.570 --> 00:11:34.990
Because SW2 learned PC1’s MAC address on
the G0/2 interface, it will send the frame

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:38.100
out of that interface toward SW1.

00:11:38.100 --> 00:11:45.640
SW1 receives the frame, and since it has already
learned PC1’s MAC address on the G0/0 interface,

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:51.630
it simply forwards the frame out of the interface,
and PC1 finally receives the ARP reply.

00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:58.029
PC1 will then use that information to add
an entry for PC3 to its ARP table, which is

00:11:58.029 --> 00:12:01.710
used to store these IP address to MAC address
associations.

00:12:01.710 --> 00:12:05.960
Let’s take a look at an ARP table.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:10.400
This is a screenshot of part of the ARP table
from my PC.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:16.920
I use Windows on my PC, but you can use the
arp -a command to view the ARP table, whether

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:22.110
you run Windows, macOS, or Linux on your computer.

00:12:22.110 --> 00:12:25.910
The Internet address column displays IP addresses.

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:32.060
The Physical address column displays the MAC
addresses that correspond to the IP addresses.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:37.380
If the type column displays static, it means
that it is a default entry, it wasn’t actually

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.020
learned by sending an ARP request.

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:45.470
However, if the type column displays dynamic,
that means that the entry was learned by sending

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:49.270
an ARP request and receiving an ARP reply.

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:56.200
You can see one entry like that here, with
an IP address of 192.168.0.1 and its MAC address

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:57.600
next to it.

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:00.870
That’s the address of my home router, by
the way.

00:13:00.870 --> 00:13:05.840
My PC used ARP to learn the MAC address of
the router.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:10.110
Now let’s take a deeper look at the MAC
address table that is kept on these switches,

00:13:10.110 --> 00:13:12.010
and some additional information.

00:13:12.010 --> 00:13:17.890
I recreated the same topology in the network
emulator software GNS3.

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:23.810
GNS3 is similar to packet tracer in that it
allows you to create networks and practice

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:30.110
configurations on Cisco devices, but its also
different in some key ways.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:34.430
Packet tracer is a network simulator, it’s
a piece of software designed to simulate the

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:36.670
operation of a real network.

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:45.220
GNS3, however, runs actual Cisco IOS software,
so these are real Cisco switches running virtually.

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:52.650
However, GNS3 requires you to purchase your
own copies of Cisco IOS, so although GNS3

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:57.650
itself is free, using Cisco IOS with GNS3
is not.

00:13:57.650 --> 00:14:03.150
That’s why I choose to use packet tracer
for the lab videos in this series, its totally

00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:07.730
free, and it lets you practice just about
everything you need for the CCNA.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:13.150
I also want to show you GNS3 sometimes in
these videos, however, since you’ll probably

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:16.800
want to use it later as you progress in your
networking studies.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:22.760
Don’t worry about using GNS3 for now though, unless
you really want to try it out.

00:14:22.760 --> 00:14:26.900
You can get it at gns3.com.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:32.100
So, here’s our topology, and notice this
magnifying glass here.

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:38.260
This is a cool feature of GNS3, it integrates
with another piece of software called wireshark,

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:43.260
and we’ll use it to analyze exactly what
traffic passes between PC1 and SW1.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:48.470
I’m going to send a ping from PC1 to PC3.

00:14:48.470 --> 00:14:53.630
The process is the same, but let me just run
down one more time what happens.

00:14:53.630 --> 00:14:59.040
Just like our example before, PC1 doesn’t
know the destination MAC address, so has to

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:01.670
send an ARP request.

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:05.220
The ARP request is sent to all other hosts
on the network.

00:15:05.220 --> 00:15:11.750
PC3 responds to the Arp request, since it’s
IP address matches the destination IP address

00:15:11.750 --> 00:15:13.840
in the ARP request.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:20.870
PC1 then learns the MAC Address of PC3, adds
it to its ARP table, and uses that information

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:24.940
to add the destination MAC Address to the
ping it wants to send.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:30.460
Now, before I move on, you may have heard
of ping before, but let me explain how it

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:32.630
works.

00:15:32.630 --> 00:15:35.260
Ping is something you’re going to be using a lot.

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:40.520
It's a network utility that is used to test
reachability, for example, to test if two

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:43.550
computers can reach each other.

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:51.610
It measures the round-trip time, for example
the time from PC1 to PC3, then back to PC1.

00:15:51.610 --> 00:16:00.360
Much like ARP, ping uses two messages: ICMP
Echo request, and ICMP echo reply.

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:04.830
Again, this is similar to an ARP request and
ARP reply.

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:11.610
However, the PC won’t broadcast the ICMP
echo request, it is sent to a specific host.

00:16:11.610 --> 00:16:16.930
So, it has to know the MAC address of the
destination host, which is why ARP must be

00:16:16.930 --> 00:16:19.130
used first.

00:16:19.130 --> 00:16:25.480
The command to use ping is ping, followed
by the IP address you want to ping to, for example,

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:30.360
192.168.1.3 for PC3 in our network.

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:34.100
Let’s take a look at the ping process.

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:36.930
So I’m on PC1 here.

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:40.310
Note that this is actually the Cisco IOS CLI.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:46.160
I’m using Cisco routers to simulate PCs,
since its easier than setting up virtual PCs

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:49.110
to ping in GNS3.

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:58.030
I use the command ping 192.168.1.3, to send
an IMCP echo request to PC3.

00:16:58.030 --> 00:17:00.270
Take a look at this message here.

00:17:00.270 --> 00:17:07.520
Sending 5, 100-byte ICMP echos to 192.168.1.3.

00:17:07.620 --> 00:17:14.860
By default, a ping in Cisco IOS sends 5 ICMP
echo requests, and then you should get 5 ICMP

00:17:14.860 --> 00:17:20.550
echo replies back, and the default size of
each ping is 100 bytes.

00:17:20.550 --> 00:17:28.630
The period indicates a failed ping, and the
exclamation points indicate a successful ping.

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:33.840
As it says here, success rate is 80 percent,
4 out of 5.

00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:39.120
It also shows the round trip time, giving
the minimum, average, and maximum time of

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:41.210
the 4 successful pings.

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:43.960
Now, why did that first ping fail?

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.330
Well, that’s because of ARP.

00:17:46.330 --> 00:17:52.520
PC1 didn’t know the destination MAC address,
so it had to use ARP, and in that time the

00:17:52.520 --> 00:17:55.020
first ping failed.

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:59.590
After PC1 learned PC3’s MAC address, however,
the pings succeeded.

00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:03.630
Let’s take a quick look at the arp table
here.

00:18:03.630 --> 00:18:08.330
The command for windows, macos, and linux
was arp -a.

00:18:08.330 --> 00:18:14.630
However, in Cisco IOS its show arp, from privileged
exec mode.

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:17.520
Here’s the ARP table.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:26.900
Notice there is an entry for 192.168.1.1,
which is PC1 itself, and then below it 192.168.1.3,

00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:30.200
which is PC3.

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:35.170
This is a screenshot from Wireshark, which
I mentioned earlier.

00:18:35.170 --> 00:18:39.770
Wireshark allows you to perform what are called
‘packet captures’, to analyze the contents

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:42.380
of network traffic.

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:44.020
Notice the Protocol column.

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:48.600
ARP, followed by ICMP, which is ping.

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:51.620
Here’s the first ARP packet.

00:18:51.620 --> 00:18:59.940
The source MAC is 0c2f b011 9d00, which is
PC1’s MAC.

00:18:59.940 --> 00:19:04.270
The destination is broadcast, which is all Fs.

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:06.610
Look at the info on the end.

00:19:06.610 --> 00:19:13.810
Who has 192.168.1.3? tell 192.168.1.1.

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:16.910
This describes what purpose of ARP is.

00:19:16.910 --> 00:19:24.700
The ARP request is asking which MAC address
has an IP address of 192.168.1.3, and to send

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:29.790
the reply to itself, 192.168.1.1.

00:19:29.790 --> 00:19:31.910
Next is the ARP reply.

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:43.770
The source address is 0c2f b06a 3900, PC3’s
MAC, and the destination is PC1’s MAC.

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:47.040
Look at the info section again here.

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:58.370
192.168.1.3 is at 0c2f b06a 3900, it’s telling
PC1 its MAC address.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:04.540
After that there are 4 ICMP echo requests,
and 4 ICMP echo replies.

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:11.900
Note that the ICMP echo requests have a source
IP of PC1 and destination of PC3, and the

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:17.559
ICMP echo replies have a source of PC3 and
destination of PC1.

00:20:17.559 --> 00:20:23.250
I’ll use wireshark at various points throughout
this course, but I think you can see how useful

00:20:23.250 --> 00:20:25.679
it can be in analyzing networks.

00:20:25.679 --> 00:20:30.470
Okay, hopefully you understand this process
a little better now.

00:20:30.470 --> 00:20:36.520
Basically, if device A wants to send traffic
to device B. which is on the same network,

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:42.410
device A first has to use ARP to learn device
B’s MAC address, and then it can send traffic

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:49.050
to device B. Now, let’s finally take a look
at the MAC address table on a Cisco switch.

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:50.670
Here it is.

00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:56.730
This is the command to view it, show mac SPACE
address HYPHEN table.

00:20:56.730 --> 00:21:04.370
Old versions of Cisco IOS use show mac hyphen
address hyphen table, but newer versions got

00:21:04.370 --> 00:21:11.800
rid of the first hyphen, and now its this,
show mac space address hyphen table.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:16.360
Now let’s look at each section of the MAC
address table, before I only showed the MAC

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:18.770
address and interface.

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:20.480
First is the VLAN.

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:24.150
VLAN means VIRTUAL local area network.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:31.100
We’ll learn about those later, but as is
displayed here the default is 1.

00:21:31.100 --> 00:21:37.929
Next is the MAC address column, you can see
PC1 up top and PC3 on the bottom, Next is

00:21:37.929 --> 00:21:40.070
the type.

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:43.240
Remember what I said about dynamic mac addresses?

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:46.870
Well it is displayed in the MAC address table
as well.

00:21:46.870 --> 00:21:52.440
Both of these MAC addresses were learned dynamically,
I did not manually configure them on the switch.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:57.310
Finally, ports, which is another word for
interface.

00:21:57.310 --> 00:22:02.840
So, you can see that this matches the small
MAC address table I put here in this diagram

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:03.840
earlier.

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:09.860
Here’s the entry for PC1, and here’s the
entry to PC2.

00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:15.530
Now, I mentioned in the previous video that
these dynamic MAC addresses are removed from

00:22:15.530 --> 00:22:18.990
the MAC address table after 5 minutes.

00:22:18.990 --> 00:22:21.430
This is known as aging.

00:22:21.430 --> 00:22:26.000
If the switch doesn’t get any traffic from
that MAC address for 5 minutes, it will remove

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.480
the entry from the MAC address table.

00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:33.630
However, you can also manually remove MAC
addresses from the table.

00:22:33.630 --> 00:22:41.170
Here I used the show mac address table command
and you can see the entries for PC1 and PC3.

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:45.710
Then I used the command clear mac address-table
dynamic.

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:50.290
As you can see, all of the dynamic MAC address
have been cleared.

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:55.260
Remember this command clear mac address-table
dynamic.

00:22:55.260 --> 00:23:00.049
Now, if you don’t want to clear all of the
mac addresses from the table, you can add

00:23:00.049 --> 00:23:03.270
some additional options to the command.

00:23:03.270 --> 00:23:08.240
Once again, I used show mac address-table,
and you can see both entries, for PC1 and

00:23:08.240 --> 00:23:09.850
PC3.

00:23:09.850 --> 00:23:15.179
This time I used a different command, clear
mac address-table dynamic address, followed

00:23:15.179 --> 00:23:18.230
by PC1’s MAC address.

00:23:18.230 --> 00:23:23.830
Then if I use show mac address-table again,
only PC3’s MAC address can be seen.

00:23:23.830 --> 00:23:26.670
Here’s the command once more.

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:31.940
Clear mac address-table dynamic address, then
the mac address.

00:23:31.940 --> 00:23:35.850
Finally, one more option to clear the MAC
address table.

00:23:35.850 --> 00:23:42.580
Again, show mac address-table shows both PC1
and PC3’s MAC addresses.

00:23:42.580 --> 00:23:50.890
This time I use the command clear mac address-table
dynamic interface gi0/0.

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:55.680
This clears all mac address table entries
for a specific interface.

00:23:55.680 --> 00:24:01.490
As you can see, once again PC1’s mac address
is removed, because it is connected to the

00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:03.070
G0/0 interface.

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:05.730
Here’s the command again.

00:24:05.730 --> 00:24:11.650
Clear mac address-table dynamic interface,
and then the interface.

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:16.240
Before we move on to the quiz, I want to show
you a little more in wireshark, regarding

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:20.980
what I said in the beginning of this video
about the Ethernet frame.

00:24:20.980 --> 00:24:28.921
In this packet capture I sent a 36-byte ping
with the command ‘ping 192.168.1.3 SIZE

00:24:28.921 --> 00:24:30.590
36’.

00:24:30.590 --> 00:24:34.970
First, notice the TYPE field down here.

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:42.340
As I mentioned in the last video, IPv4’s
ethernet type is 0x0800.

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:48.900
The 0x just means that its using hexadecimal,
so really its 0800.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:52.429
Next, look at the padding here.

00:24:52.429 --> 00:24:59.940
Remember, the minimum payload size for an
ethernet frame is 46 bytes, and I sent 36

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:04.490
byte pings, so there should be 10 bytes of
padding.

00:25:04.490 --> 00:25:07.809
These zeroes are hexadecimal zeroes.

00:25:07.809 --> 00:25:15.600
Each hexadecimal digit is 4 bits, so 2 digits
equals 8 bits, or 1 byte.

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:22.690
If you count the zeroes, there are 20 zeroes,
so that means 10 bytes of padding.

00:25:22.690 --> 00:25:27.030
If I zoom out a bit you can also see the padding
down here.

00:25:27.030 --> 00:25:32.380
These ten pairs of zeroes are the 10 bytes
of padding added to the 36-byte pings to make

00:25:32.380 --> 00:25:35.890
them meet the 46-byte payload minimum size.

00:25:35.890 --> 00:25:38.800
One last thing in wireshark.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:40.780
This time looking at ARP.

00:25:40.780 --> 00:25:50.490
Remember, the IPv4 ethernet type is 0800,
and the IPv6 ethernet type is 86DD.

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:56.500
As you can see here, the ARP ethernet type
of 0806.

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:00.390
This indicates that an ARP packet is inside
of this ethernet frame.

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:05.740
Okay, so we covered a lot of important stuff
in this video.

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:10.981
We talked about some more details of the ethernet
frame, including the minimum size of the ethernet

00:26:10.981 --> 00:26:14.679
payload, which is 46 bytes.

00:26:14.679 --> 00:26:18.710
We talked about ARP, the address resolution
protocol.

00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:24.330
It is used to learn the MAC address of a device,
for which you already know the IP address.

00:26:24.330 --> 00:26:31.100
It uses two messages, an ARP request, which
is broadcast to all devices on the local network,

00:26:31.100 --> 00:26:36.480
and an ARP reply, which is sent to the device
which sent the request.

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:42.440
We also looked at the ARP table on a windows
device and a Cisco IOS device.

00:26:42.440 --> 00:26:47.260
We talked about ping, which is used to test
reachability in a network.

00:26:47.260 --> 00:26:54.250
It also uses two messages, ICMP echo request
and ICMP echo reply.

00:26:54.250 --> 00:26:59.430
Finally, we looked at the MAC address table
on a Cisco switch, including how to clear

00:26:59.430 --> 00:27:01.400
it in a few ways.

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:04.750
Let’s move on to the quiz for today’s
video.

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:08.120
Here’s question 1.

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:13.090
You send a 36-byte ping to another computer
and perform a packet capture to analyze the

00:27:13.090 --> 00:27:15.380
network traffic.

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:23.929
You notice a long series of bytes of 00000000
at the end of the Ethernet payload.

00:27:23.929 --> 00:27:26.450
How can you explain these zeroes?

00:27:26.450 --> 00:27:30.360
A, pings are a series of zeroes.

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:34.110
B, they are padding bytes.

00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:38.140
Or C, they are the Ethernet FCS.

00:27:38.140 --> 00:27:44.040
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:47.880
the answer is B, they are padding bytes.

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:54.970
The ping you sent was 36 bytes, but the minimum
Ethernet payload size is 46 bytes, so a series

00:27:54.970 --> 00:27:58.620
of padding bytes must be added to meet the
minimum payload size.

00:27:58.620 --> 00:28:03.160
Let’s go to question 2.

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:07.460
Which of these messages is sent to all hosts
on the local network?

00:28:07.460 --> 00:28:10.350
A, ARP Requeset.

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:13.190
B, arp reply.

00:28:13.190 --> 00:28:16.830
C, icmp echo request.

00:28:16.830 --> 00:28:20.420
Or D, ICMP echo reply.

00:28:20.420 --> 00:28:26.559
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:28:26.559 --> 00:28:29.630
the answer is a, ARP request.

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:31.539
Let’s check.

00:28:31.539 --> 00:28:37.090
The ARP reply message is a unicast message
sent to the host that sent the ARP request.

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:41.210
So b, ARP reply, is incorrect.

00:28:41.210 --> 00:28:47.150
The ICMP echo request is a unicast message
used to test the reachability of another specific

00:28:47.150 --> 00:28:48.590
host.

00:28:48.590 --> 00:28:53.070
The ICMP echo reply is a unicast reply to
the request.

00:28:53.070 --> 00:28:59.961
So C, ICMP echo request, and D, ICMP echo
reply, the two messages used in PING, are

00:28:59.961 --> 00:29:02.470
incorrect.

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:07.330
The ARP request message is used to learn the
Layer 2 address of a host.

00:29:07.330 --> 00:29:12.370
Because the Layer 2 address is not yet known,
the message has to be broadcast to all hosts

00:29:12.370 --> 00:29:14.309
on the local network.

00:29:14.309 --> 00:29:17.440
So A, ARP request, is the correct answer.

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:21.520
Let’s go to question 3.

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:26.220
Which fields are present in the output of
the show mac address-table command on a Cisco

00:29:26.220 --> 00:29:27.380
switch?

00:29:27.380 --> 00:29:30.770
A, mac address, and ports.

00:29:30.770 --> 00:29:35.320
B, VLAN, mac address, and ports.

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:40.830
C, VLAN, MAC address, type, and ports.

00:29:40.830 --> 00:29:46.200
D, Internet address, physical address, and
type.

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:52.890
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:29:52.890 --> 00:29:57.600
The answer is C, VLAN, MAC address, type,
and ports.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:29:59.570
Let’s take a look.

00:29:59.570 --> 00:30:04.950
Here’s a screenshot of the MAC address table
on a Cisco switch.

00:30:04.950 --> 00:30:10.480
Notice the four fields, VLAN, MAC address,
type, and ports.

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:13.919
So C is the correct answer.

00:30:13.919 --> 00:30:19.929
By the way, answer D, Internet address, physical
address, and type, is the output shown from

00:30:19.929 --> 00:30:24.150
the arp -a command on my windows PC.

00:30:24.150 --> 00:30:29.250
This is part of the ARP table on my PC, not
the MAC address table on a Cisco switch.

00:30:29.250 --> 00:30:33.140
Let’s go to question 4

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:37.730
Which types of frames does a switch send out
of all interfaces, except the one the frame

00:30:37.730 --> 00:30:39.580
was received on?

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:43.520
A, broadcast and unknown unicast.

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:47.660
B, broadcast and known unicast.

00:30:47.660 --> 00:30:52.280
C, known unicast and unknown unicast.

00:30:52.280 --> 00:30:57.660
Or D, broadcast, unknown unicast, and known
unicast.

00:30:57.660 --> 00:31:03.750
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:07.380
the answer is A, broadcast and unknown unicast.

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:09.160
Let’s check.

00:31:09.160 --> 00:31:13.620
Known unicast frames are sent to a single
host.

00:31:13.620 --> 00:31:17.990
Because the switch already has an entry for
the destination in its MAC address table,

00:31:17.990 --> 00:31:21.560
there is no need to flood the frame out all
interfaces.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:28.740
So B, C, and D are incorrect because they
include known unicast.

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:37.600
Broadcast frames have a destination address
of FFFF.FFFF.FFFF and are sent to all hosts

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:40.220
on the local network.

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:44.480
Unknown unicast frames are destined for a
single host, however the switch doesn’t

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:50.100
have an entry for the destination in its MAC
address table so it must flood the frame.

00:31:50.100 --> 00:31:54.799
So A, broadcast and unknown unicast, is the
correct answer.

00:31:54.799 --> 00:32:00.059
Lets’ go to the last question for today’s
video.

00:32:00.059 --> 00:32:05.260
Which command is used on a Cisco switch to
clear all dynamic MAC addresses on a specific

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:08.540
interface from the MAC address table?

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:15.320
A, clear mac address HYPHEN table interface,
interface-id.

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:24.240
B, clear mac HYPHEN address HYPHEN table dynamic
interface, interface-id.

00:32:24.240 --> 00:32:31.960
C, clear mac HYPHEN address table dynamic
interface, interface-id.

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:39.620
or D, clear mac address HYPHEN table dynamic
interface, interface ID.

00:32:39.620 --> 00:32:45.460
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:53.120
the answer is D, clear mac address HYPHEN
table dynamic interface interface-id.

